\#\#\# Theme 1: Growth Treadmill

\*\*Headline:\*\* "The Growth Treadmill"

\*\*Body content:\*\* Reference churn rate, replacement revenue dollar amount and %, replacement clients needed, team utilization/capacity, and cash runway. Make the math concrete and impossible to miss.

\*\*Example body:\*\* "Your 3% monthly churn creates $28.5K annual replacement revenue requirement to maintain $1.2M scale — consuming 36% of your revenue base before any growth. With 28 active clients, this means closing 10 new clients per year just to stay flat. At 70% team utilization with founder split between delivery and operations, growth beyond replacement requires either strategic hiring or full founder transition — and 0.5-month cash runway limits hiring flexibility."

\*\*So what:\*\* Frame as "you're running uphill" — growth targets must account for replacement first, and capacity/cash constrain climb speed.

\#\#\# Theme 2: Cash-Margin Disconnect

\*\*Headline:\*\* "Cash-Margin Disconnect" or "Profitability Without Liquidity"

\*\*Body content:\*\* Reference operating margin, cash runway, what creates the disconnect (project timing, AR/AP, distributions, replacement revenue consuming cash generation).

\*\*Example body:\*\* "Your 32% operating margin generates $22K monthly profit, but 0.4-month cash runway reveals a disconnect: profitability isn't translating to liquidity. With $28.5K annual replacement revenue requirement from churn, profit is consumed by the growth treadmill before building reserves. This explains strong margins alongside critical cash position."

\*\*So what:\*\* Strong margins don't translate to strategic flexibility when cash is tied up. Growth investment structurally constrained despite profitability.

\#\#\# Theme 3: Concentration Dependency

\*\*Headline:\*\* "Concentration Dependency" or "Key Account Vulnerability"

\*\*Body content:\*\* Reference concentration %, number of clients, cash runway, founder involvement, ACV level. Characterize what concentration creates/requires.

\*\*Example body:\*\* "With 70% of revenue concentrated in your top 5 clients and 0.4-month cash runway, a single key account loss creates existential liquidity pressure before replacement revenue materializes. At $12.5K ACV with founder still in delivery, these relationships require personal stewardship. Your business model isn't a diversification problem — it's a relationship-intensive operation where key account retention is the growth foundation."

\*\*So what:\*\* Business stability depends on relationship continuity at the founder level. Delegation must account for maintaining key accounts.

\#\#\# Theme 4: Service-Structure Alignment

\*\*Headline:\*\* "Service-Structure Alignment" or "Model-Structure Tension"

\*\*Body content:\*\* Reference positioning (specialist vs generalist), industry count, ACV level, team structure type, management layers. Note alignment or misalignment.

\*\*Example body:\*\* "Your specialist positioning in 2 regulated industries suggests deep vertical expertise, but your mostly-generalist team structure with flat management creates a tension: clients likely expect specialist depth, but delivery model is built for flexibility across diverse needs. At $8.5K ACV, client complexity may be outpacing team specialization infrastructure."

\*\*So what:\*\* If intentional hybrid model, it requires strong coordination. If unintentional, it signals either team evolution needed or positioning refinement.

\#\#\# Theme 5: Founder Transition Imperative

\*\*Headline:\*\* "Founder Transition Imperative" or "Delegation Ceiling"

\*\*Body content:\*\* Reference founder time allocation, AGI/revenue scale, team size, concentration, leadership infrastructure present/absent.

\*\*Example body:\*\* "At $2.8M AGI with 35-person team, you've scaled beyond typical founder-delivery limits, yet founder remains primarily in client work. With 65% revenue concentration in top 5 clients and no COO or Operations Director in place, key account retention and delivery oversight remain founder-dependent. This configuration creates a delegation ceiling: further scale requires leadership infrastructure that can maintain client relationships and delivery quality without founder's direct involvement."

\*\*So what:\*\* Founder time is the constraint on next growth phase. Delegation infrastructure (not just more team) is the unlock.

\#\# Section 4: Operating Implications (4-6 Bullets)

Translate the 3 Critical Insights into concrete structural requirements.

Frame as: "Operating at your current state requires:"

\*\*Pull bullets from the selected insight themes:\*\*

\*\*If Growth Treadmill selected:\*\*  
\- "$\[amount\] annual replacement revenue to offset churn (before any growth)"  
\- "\[X\] new clients per year at current ACV to maintain scale"  
\- "Strategic hiring or founder delegation to expand beyond \[X\]% utilization" (if capacity constrained)

\*\*If Cash-Margin Disconnect selected:\*\*  
\- "Tight cash flow management with \[X\]-month buffer limiting hiring/investment flexibility"  
\- "Active AR collection discipline to convert profitability to liquidity" (if AR data present)

\*\*If Concentration Dependency selected:\*\*  
\- "Active management of top \[X\] client relationships representing \[Y\]% of revenue"  
\- "Founder stewardship of key accounts given concentration dynamics"

\*\*If Service-Structure Alignment selected:\*\*  
\- "Team specialization development or positioning refinement to align model and structure"

\*\*If Founder Transition selected:\*\*  
\- "Leadership infrastructure development to enable founder delegation"  
\- "Founder involvement in delivery oversight and key account retention" (if still in delivery)

\*\*Select 4-6 most operationally significant bullets\*\* across the 3 themes.

\*\*Length:\*\* 4-6 bullets, \~10-15 words each

\#\# Tone Guidelines

\*\*Write like:\*\* A McKinsey consultant presenting the synthesis of a multi-week diagnostic engagement

\*\*NOT like:\*\* A business coach giving advice, a consultant selling services, or a report summarizing findings

\*\*Language to use:\*\* "characterized by," "creates," "requires," "generates," "positions," "operates," "maintains," "depends on," "constrains," "enables"

\*\*Language to NEVER use:\*\* "you should," "we recommend," "you need to," "to scale you must," "this is a problem," "you're doing wrong"

\*\*When noting tensions or misalignments:\*\* Frame as structural observations, not judgments. "This creates X requirement" not "this is preventing Y."

